00:40:01.320 --> 00:40:03.566
That's how you want to
present yourself to the world.

00:40:03.566 --> 00:40:04.940
But you don't see
a lot of what's

00:40:04.940 --> 00:40:06.148
really going on all the time.

00:40:06.148 --> 00:40:08.650
And I'm not going to
bash a job if it's not

00:40:08.650 --> 00:40:10.300
going well on Instagram.

00:40:10.300 --> 00:40:13.120
So you're just going to
see me looking great.

00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:16.810
But I do think it is a little
bit deceiving that things

00:40:16.810 --> 00:40:18.730
look so great all the time.

00:40:18.730 --> 00:40:21.270
I mean, I'm very appreciative
of my life and all that.

00:40:21.270 --> 00:40:23.394
But there's this
thing in culture

00:40:23.394 --> 00:40:25.060
now where I feel like
everyone's feeling

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:26.670
this fear of missing out.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:31.230
And I just want to remind
people that it's all a fantasy.

00:40:34.250 --> 00:40:35.927
JASON WU: Models eat, too.

00:40:35.927 --> 00:40:37.260
We're going to have pizza later.

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:38.160
MARTHA HUNT: Yes, and
I also try to show

00:40:38.160 --> 00:40:39.910
that I work out a lot
because I think it's

00:40:39.910 --> 00:40:41.460
important to motivate people.

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:43.930
That helps people get
inspired to get to the gym.

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:47.330
And it takes a lot of work
to maintain my figure.

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:49.890
I'm not trying to act like,
oh, I eat whatever I want.

00:40:49.890 --> 00:40:51.480
And I'm tall and
thin and all that.

00:40:51.480 --> 00:40:53.520
I definitely work
out and work for it.

00:40:53.520 --> 00:40:54.936
AUDIENCE: I think
that's been more

00:40:54.936 --> 00:40:57.060
of a trend, though,
of people-- a lot

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:01.360
of models being more
open about that and about

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:04.090
how much work it takes
to eat healthfully

00:41:04.090 --> 00:41:06.920
to-- especially while
traveling and your lifestyle

00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:07.800
is so demanding.

00:41:07.800 --> 00:41:10.981
And that's hard
for someone going

00:41:10.981 --> 00:41:12.480
to work at the same
job every single

00:41:12.480 --> 00:41:14.880
day and workplace let alone
traveling all over the world

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:16.950
and not having any of
your comforts around.

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:18.040
MARTHA HUNT:
Understandably, yeah.

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:20.498
AUDIENCE: So it's nice that
there's so much exposure there.

00:41:20.498 --> 00:41:22.975
JASON WU: I mean, you and Karlie
inspire me to go work out.

00:41:22.975 --> 00:41:24.100
MARTHA HUNT: Oh, thank you.

00:41:24.100 --> 00:41:26.099
JASON WU: You guys are
always going to work out.

00:41:26.099 --> 00:41:28.016
I finally got my ass out
to the gym this year.

00:41:28.016 --> 00:41:29.098
MARTHA HUNT: Always, yeah.

00:41:29.098 --> 00:41:30.320
JASON WU: Everything's wrong.

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:32.180
MARTHA HUNT: But there's also
a tremendous amount of pressure

00:41:32.180 --> 00:41:32.926
to post.

00:41:32.926 --> 00:41:34.300
Sometimes I feel
like, oh, I feel

00:41:34.300 --> 00:41:37.470
like I'm so annoying putting
all this content out there.

00:41:37.470 --> 00:41:40.050
But we're also getting
pressure from our agencies.

00:41:40.050 --> 00:41:40.930
We need more content.

00:41:40.930 --> 00:41:42.820
Show your personality,
because it's

00:41:42.820 --> 00:41:45.310
designers like Jason
who are casting

00:41:45.310 --> 00:41:47.394
girls that have a following.

00:41:47.394 --> 00:41:49.810
It's become such a key role
in our industry for the model.

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:51.018
JASON WU: Yeah, so important.

00:41:51.018 --> 00:41:53.407
MARTHA HUNT: Yeah,
it's so important.

00:41:53.407 --> 00:41:54.240
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:55.244
MARTHA HUNT: Thank you.

00:41:55.244 --> 00:41:55.785
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:55.785 --> 00:41:58.770
I have a question about
dressing celebrities.

00:41:58.770 --> 00:42:01.360
You talked a little bit about
seeing the person walking down

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:02.776
the street on the
Upper East Side.

00:42:02.776 --> 00:42:04.040
And that gave you joy.

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:06.640
But then how do
you reconcile when

00:42:06.640 --> 00:42:09.690
we talk about awards seasons and
all these different big events,

00:42:09.690 --> 00:42:12.780
and you have very high profile
people wearing your clothes.

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:14.010
What does that feel like?

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:15.590
Is that the same level?

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:17.240
Is that the same level of joy?

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:20.460
Or is that not as
important to you anymore?

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:23.650
Because I think you've dressed
First Ladies and all of that.

00:42:23.650 --> 00:42:25.600
Is there an aspirational
piece, like I

00:42:25.600 --> 00:42:28.120
want to dress this
person, but it's also

00:42:28.120 --> 00:42:30.480
interesting to see normal
people wearing my clothes?

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:30.540
How does that feel?

00:42:30.540 --> 00:42:31.220
JASON WU: I think it's both.

00:42:31.220 --> 00:42:32.090
I mean, I think it's different.

00:42:32.090 --> 00:42:34.232
I love seeing people wear
my clothes in general.

00:42:34.232 --> 00:42:35.815
It's two very different
things, right?

00:42:38.390 --> 00:42:40.790
I love seeing-- I go
to stores all the time.

00:42:40.790 --> 00:42:42.460
I interact with my customers.

00:42:42.460 --> 00:42:43.530
I dress them.

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:46.580
And I suggest.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:47.702
I'm very blunt.

00:42:47.702 --> 00:42:50.160
So if something doesn't look
good on her, I would just say,

00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:51.970
don't buy it.

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:56.350
I'm very-- I love that
process of working with people

00:42:56.350 --> 00:42:59.360
and making them feel
great and look amazing.

00:42:59.360 --> 00:43:03.320
And seeing my work on them
makes me feel very good.

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:04.680
Award season is different.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:11.340
For me, from I would say a
small brand point of view,

00:43:11.340 --> 00:43:16.130
a lot of what red carpet has
become is product placement.

00:43:16.130 --> 00:43:19.290
And a lot of actors
are endorsing brands.

00:43:19.290 --> 00:43:24.060
And for me, for my own
brand, almost, I would say,

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:26.010
all the actresses
and people I dress

00:43:26.010 --> 00:43:28.090
are people I have a
relationship with.

00:43:28.090 --> 00:43:31.610
So to me, it becomes about
me helping them accomplish

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:34.100
something at a moment
that's important to them,

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:35.580
me making them look the best.

00:43:35.580 --> 00:43:36.120
MARTHA HUNT: Very exciting.

00:43:36.120 --> 00:43:38.530
JASON WU: And so it's a little
bit more personal for me.

00:43:38.530 --> 00:43:42.120
And it makes me feel very
proud if a friend of mine

00:43:42.120 --> 00:43:45.730
wins something and
she's wearing my design.

00:43:45.730 --> 00:43:48.930
I feel like part of the success.

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:54.920
So my goal has always been
more a personal one, I guess.

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:59.810
So, yeah, I still get a rush
seeing something very public

00:43:59.810 --> 00:44:04.440
happen, something I'm very
proud of my friend for doing,

00:44:04.440 --> 00:44:08.255
and that I can be a part of that
through making her look great.

00:44:08.255 --> 00:44:10.380
MARTHA HUNT: Could you
share an example of a friend

00:44:10.380 --> 00:44:12.088
that you were really
excited that you got

00:44:12.088 --> 00:44:13.810
to dress in an exciting moment?

00:44:13.810 --> 00:44:16.394
JASON WU: I mean,
Kerry Washington,

00:44:16.394 --> 00:44:18.310
she's been my friend for
like-- she's actually

00:44:18.310 --> 00:44:20.650
one of the first
actresses to ever wear me.

00:44:23.980 --> 00:44:25.970
So I met her about
nine years ago.

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:28.560
MARTHA HUNT: She's stunning.

00:44:28.560 --> 00:44:32.100
JASON WU: A couple years ago,
she was going to the Oscars.

00:44:32.100 --> 00:44:35.870
And she's pregnant
with her first baby.

00:44:35.870 --> 00:44:39.290
It was really her moment.

00:44:39.290 --> 00:44:42.100
She was presenting,
and people were just

00:44:42.100 --> 00:44:44.390
throwing everything at her.

00:44:44.390 --> 00:44:46.065
And this is very rare.

00:44:46.065 --> 00:44:48.690
Three months before the Oscars,
she asked me to make her dress.

00:44:48.690 --> 00:44:52.090
And she never changed her mind.

00:44:52.090 --> 00:44:54.370
That sounds maybe not
like so much right

00:44:54.370 --> 00:44:58.310
now, but, honestly, actresses
get so much given to them,

00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:02.010
that they can change
their mind at any moment

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:03.680
in the last minute.

00:45:03.680 --> 00:45:06.210
And she did that.

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:09.145
And it was really a
very special moment.

00:45:09.145 --> 00:45:11.020
AUDIENCE: What about
dressing the First Lady?

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:12.341
How's that like?

00:45:12.341 --> 00:45:13.090
JASON WU: Amazing.

00:45:13.090 --> 00:45:18.500
I mean, to be able to-- for me,
as an Asian-American Canadian

00:45:18.500 --> 00:45:25.160
person, to be an immigrant,
to be the first Asian person

00:45:25.160 --> 00:45:29.210
to dress the first
African-American First Lady is

00:45:29.210 --> 00:45:30.760
super significant to me.

00:45:30.760 --> 00:45:33.450
I never imagined that
that's something I

00:45:33.450 --> 00:45:34.760
would be able to be a part of.

00:45:34.760 --> 00:45:39.070
I wanted it to be in "Vogue."

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:40.827
But after that
experience, I started

00:45:40.827 --> 00:45:42.410
thinking so much
bigger, like thinking

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:45.634
about how there's so much--

00:45:45.634 --> 00:45:47.550
MARTHA HUNT: How many
more boxes can you tick?

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:51.634
JASON WU: I mean, though,
it just humbled me a lot.

00:45:51.634 --> 00:45:52.300
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:53.040
Hey.

00:45:53.040 --> 00:45:54.290
Thanks so much for being here.

00:45:54.290 --> 00:45:55.110
This is great.

00:45:55.110 --> 00:45:56.380
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:56.380 --> 00:45:59.200
I had a question
around the price point.

00:45:59.200 --> 00:46:01.700
You mentioned earlier
that even sometimes you

00:46:01.700 --> 00:46:04.460
think you can't afford
your own clothes, right?

00:46:04.460 --> 00:46:07.770
And I understand completely that
good quality, craftsmanship,

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:11.040
and materials, and design,
et cetera, in any field--

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:13.810
whether that's clothing or
food or anything-- costs a lot

00:46:13.810 --> 00:46:14.450
of money.

00:46:14.450 --> 00:46:16.350
Have you ever
thought about trying

00:46:16.350 --> 00:46:19.200
to adapt your
lines in the future

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:21.805
to be more accessible from
a price point perspective?

00:46:21.805 --> 00:46:23.430
JASON WU: Well, I
just launched "Grey,"

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:25.596
which is the collection
that is much more accessible

00:46:25.596 --> 00:46:32.110
and a price point between $150
to $800 for an outerwear piece,

00:46:32.110 --> 00:46:33.400
for example.

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.080
So that's definitely a
different price range for me.

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:41.440
But it's still
pricey, but I think

00:46:41.440 --> 00:46:45.570
it's also made with
an understanding

00:46:45.570 --> 00:46:49.287
that it's clothes you
can keep for a long time.

00:46:49.287 --> 00:46:50.120
It's not throw-away.

00:46:50.120 --> 00:46:52.060
MARTHA HUNT: Yeah,
they're classic pieces.

00:46:52.060 --> 00:46:53.690
They're classic
investment pieces.

00:46:53.690 --> 00:46:55.773
JASON WU: They give you
fashion, but there's still

00:46:55.773 --> 00:46:57.660
a timelessness.

00:46:57.660 --> 00:46:59.890
AUDIENCE: I'm just
curious on that.

00:46:59.890 --> 00:47:01.846
What needs to be
changed to actually

00:47:01.846 --> 00:47:02.970
bring the price point down?

00:47:02.970 --> 00:47:04.730
What are the elements
that actually--

00:47:04.730 --> 00:47:06.740
JASON WU: Well, lot
of different things.

00:47:06.740 --> 00:47:10.030
I think, look, it's also just
very different kind of clothes

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:10.600
for me.

00:47:10.600 --> 00:47:12.130
Now, look, if you
see these pieces,

00:47:12.130 --> 00:47:13.213
these are from collection.

00:47:13.213 --> 00:47:14.560
These are from "Grey."

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:15.790
These are much more day.

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:19.410
They're much easier to
wear, casual shapes.

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:23.260
Here, this is very expensive
because it's a down jacket made

00:47:23.260 --> 00:47:25.720
with this feather ball fabric.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:31.780
And it's hand-embroidered over
1,000 hours, little feathers

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:33.450
encrusted on with beads.

00:47:33.450 --> 00:47:36.290
If you look at the craftsmanship
of that, that's the difference.

00:47:36.290 --> 00:47:37.873
I'm not going to be
able to bring that

00:47:37.873 --> 00:47:40.960
for a different price point.

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:45.300
But that's my obsession, the
art of creating something

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:50.855
so painstakingly made that it's
just sometimes beyond reason.

00:47:50.855 --> 00:47:52.446
AUDIENCE: OK, thanks.

00:47:52.446 --> 00:47:53.320
AUDIENCE: Hey, Jason.

00:47:53.320 --> 00:47:58.390
My question is actually very
related to the last one.

00:47:58.390 --> 00:48:01.790
So there's a certain warmth
to handmade clothing,

00:48:01.790 --> 00:48:04.170
whereas a lot of
times technology

00:48:04.170 --> 00:48:06.600
gets the stigma of
being very cold.

00:48:06.600 --> 00:48:09.210
What techniques did you
use in your collection

00:48:09.210 --> 00:48:12.870
to make the clothes still
very special and warm?

00:48:12.870 --> 00:48:18.800
JASON WU: I mean, everything
I make is made by hand.

00:48:18.800 --> 00:48:20.750
I'm a true believer in that.

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:24.500
I'm not very good at
drawing on the computer.

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:27.850
I'm much better drawing by hand.

00:48:27.850 --> 00:48:29.540
So I'm a very
hand-oriented person.

00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:32.630
I do think that's something
that will probably never

00:48:32.630 --> 00:48:35.000
change for me.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:40.320
But I mean, definitely to
use technology in fashion

00:48:40.320 --> 00:48:41.930
doesn't mean take away the hand.

00:48:41.930 --> 00:48:43.750
You can laser cut a fabric.

00:48:43.750 --> 00:48:47.020
You can treat it with some
sort of interesting coating

00:48:47.020 --> 00:48:49.600
to either change the appearance
or texture of the fabric

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:51.140
or the function of the fabric.

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:56.330
Those are things that could be
very beneficial through using

00:48:56.330 --> 00:48:57.240
technology.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:00.300
But the truth is,
there is still really

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:03.310
no such thing as
machine-made fashion.

00:49:03.310 --> 00:49:06.760
Even the T-shirt I'm wearing
or something that you think

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:08.994
is machine made, a
pair of hands still

00:49:08.994 --> 00:49:10.410
has to put it
through the machine.

00:49:10.410 --> 00:49:12.380
It doesn't really exist.

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:16.350
There's no such thing as a
machine made fashion really,

00:49:16.350 --> 00:49:18.000
not yet.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.055
AUDIENCE: Until robots
are putting clothes

00:49:20.055 --> 00:49:20.888
through the machine.

00:49:20.888 --> 00:49:24.338
JASON WU: Yeah, no, I mean,
something as simple as this,

00:49:24.338 --> 00:49:25.796
it's still made by
a pair of hands.

00:49:25.796 --> 00:49:26.900
MARTHA HUNT: That's true.

00:49:26.900 --> 00:49:27.914
That's a good point.

00:49:27.914 --> 00:49:28.580
AUDIENCE: Thanks

00:49:28.580 --> 00:49:29.530
JASON WU: Thank you.

00:49:29.530 --> 00:49:30.620
MARTHA HUNT: Thank you.

00:49:30.620 --> 00:49:32.430
Well, I think that's all
we have time for today.

00:49:32.430 --> 00:49:33.610
JASON WU: Thank
you for having us.

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:35.130
MARTHA HUNT: Thank you
guys so much for having us.

00:49:35.130 --> 00:49:35.850
It was such an honor.

00:49:35.850 --> 00:49:36.450
Thank you.

